                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/1476: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-30T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 30, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 30—1:27 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>494. My 493, November 29, 7 p.m., with regard to the recognition of Manchukuo, I
                    gather from a Foreign Office source that Japan has for months been asking Italy
                    for such recognition and that this Government had finally decided to acquiesce.
                    My informant added that he had no doubt but that Germany would shortly follow
                    Italy’s example and he also expressed the opinion that China itself would do so
                    before long. He said that he knew that China had been ready to extend
                    recognition for a considerable time but had been deterred because of British
                    influence. In conclusion he added that in view of Italy’s action “all other
                    nations could now feel free to recognize Manchukuo”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
